<Author>Mushiquino
<Content>Not for Everybody But Could Be For You Hoping to avoid the swarms of tourists and assorted tourist traps on Puerto Rico, my wife and I looked for something on the Carribean side of the island. The Carribe Playa Beach Resort -- and a rented car to explore the southern part of Puerto Rico -- sounded perfect. Yes, all my Puerto Rican friends shook their heads and asked, Patillas??? Why are you going to Patillas? but we stuck with our plan.First, the positives:The photos of this place do not lie. Caribe Playa Beach Resort really is right on the beach with some breathtaking views. Palm trees, beautiful water and sunshine we were lucky to have for our four days there -- it all looks too good to be true on the website but the views really are this amazing. There are beach chairs and hammocks all over the place to lounge around on, there is an outdoor restaurant with the same excellent views right there too. The water when we were there (November) was a very swimmable temperature. The staff was for the most part extremely helpful and friendly (more later) and the coffee in this place was excellent. The nicest thing of all isn't so much about this place as it is a commentary about the island -- I have travelled quite a bit and I have never met friendlier people than the people in Puerto Rico. We must have stopped to ask for directions a thousand times, and every time people went out of their way to help us. Strangers smiled at us and said hi. People constantly wished us good morning. There are a lot of people who are nice for the sake of being nice on this island. The not so positives: As long as you are not expecting to be pampered like a spoiled diva, most of the not so positives of the Caribe Playa Beach Resort aren't really all that bad. Still, you should know that the restaurant staff tend to take a while with your food, as in a very long time. Also, as many have mentioned, there is some noise from the traffic along the highway, which may disturb light sleepers. (I loved the sound of the surf lulling me to sleep, however). Of particular disappointment to me was the fact that the king size bed we were told we'd have was really just two twin beds stuck together and covered with a king size bed spread and sheets to make it look king size. I really wouldn't have cared if I had had to share a bed with my brother or somebody, but for my honeymoon with my wife, not having a big crack down the middle of our bed would have been nice. The water, while swimmable, is not what you might have in mind when you think, Ahhh, the Carribean. It has lots of rocks at points and it isn't clear as in snorkeling type water. Lastly, you should know that this place is FAR from the San Juan Airport, so if you have a late arriving flight, you probably won't get in until the middle of the night, and that's if you don't get lost, which we did (rather badly.)The roads on the southern part of the island are in general windy and not always in the best of shape. We ended up going north at times to Fajardo and over to San Juan anyway, where the infrastructure really did seem to be better suited to tourists. Still, we had some great views driving on the Carribean side, particularly going east of Patillas, we met friendly people wherever we were, and despite some construction down there at times as well, we felt good about getting to know the less-known side of the island. It somehow seemed more authentic, which is what we wanted.The only real negative about our stay which really was a shame and knocks this hotel down a couple of notches, was that in the middle of our second night, I awoke to hear my wife shrieking. I sat up in bed quickly -- what was it? A rat? A burglar? No. My wife was stading in a huge puddle of water. She had gotten up to use the bathroom and had instead found that the toilet had not been functioning properly -- it had kept filling its tank continuously without stopping, and had flooded our room. I walked through the water and turned off the toilet (rather proud of myself to figure out to do this after being awakened suddenly at 3 AM) and we used our towels to soak up as much of the water as we could. After the sun came up, I explained the problem to the hotel manager, who agreed to put us in a different room, but in the end, one of the maintenance guys fixed the toilet and we ended up staying in our original room. Not a huge deal, but if I were the manager of a hotel and I wanted people to come back, I would have offered us something -- a free meal at least -- if two of my guests had lost a good night's sleep and not been able to use a bathroom until the morning because one of my toilets didn't work. Instead, I had to pracically beg for this, and explain over and over to skeptical management that it wasn't us who had stopped up or damaged the toilet -- it just didn't work. In the end, they gave us a free dinner. Much appreciated. But if I hadn't complained about it, they would have done nothing. You have to go to Caribe Playa Beach Resort -- and the southern side of Puerto Rico -- with the mentality that even though it's the U.S., it's in many ways a foreign country, with all its positives and all its charm, as well as it's inconveniences that might annoy you when you aren't used to them. If you keep that in mind and are okay with that, then this place will be just fine for you (and also if you feel that toilets are overrated.) 
