<Author>gRantz
<Content>Resort? Not quite...but escape it is The area where the Caribe Playa is located is essentially a neighborhood that occasionally gets invaded by some strangers (i.e., tourists) who want nothing to do with them. The men stand around and drink all day and the women cook and clean and raise children. If the women work, they are usually getting paid to cook and clean and raise children.The hotel was basic but compared to most of the surrounding community it was grand. I wouldn't exactly call it a resort though. It was Clean, which is vital for my princess-soul to tolerate. Quiet, which is requisite or cranky won't begin to cover it. Remote, which I prefer on my anti-social sabbaticals. Of course, 6 nights and I wanted to slash my throat if I had to wake to those aqua walls one more day. The stone floors were old and stained, though there was no mold to be found. The 1970's bedspread was untouchable. Thank goodness we brought our own pillow cases (princesses learn how to take care of themsleves, dontcha know).There is some management shifting going on and Louis has been hired to come and make changes but he isn't ultimately in control. The owner's son is the Manager and he basically seems to hate working there. They do not make any concessions to the guests and whatever you do, don't expect a refund if you cut your trip short. We had a family emergency and had to cut our trip short by only one night...we asked that they take our food bill, which was about the same amount, and apply it to the night so we didn't have to fork over more moolah...forget it! I got one ridiculous reason after another from the owner's son, he was not too pleasant about it and then proceeded to avoid me on the property for the rest of my visit.If the owner's son doesn't learn a lesson about customer service, he will soon have fewer customers to deal with. The food is very very basic...and yes, you do need to make a reservation for dinner, but even late afternoon is okay and one night the restaurant we drove to was closed and when we called the hotel, they let us come in for dinner. So the staff really does try to accomodate. The beaches are rocky and a bit narrow but the water is blue as can be. The water is tub-like as expected, but choppier than we might have hoped due to the coral reefs scattered around. At first I was cranky as hell about it. But we stepped out of our room and walked about 25 feet and we were on the beach. Once I settled into my lounger and slathered on the sunscreen (we're near the equator here folks, burn happens while you're applying the stuff, ask my forehead), I was pretty darned content.The dogs ran off-leash the entire week. The place was not over-run by strays, thankfully. However one resident dog of the hotel, an old mutt, followed us around to the point of annoyance and was there at our door every morning. When we complained we were told that it had been there for over 10 years and was part of the place. Very frustrating.We asked where we could get some provisions...water, snacks and such. We were told to go to the mini-mart at the Texaco station just down the road. We eventually found the town centre of Patillas and the local grocery store. The Texaco was indeed the better option.One place you must go to pick up food is the bakery in town. Louis will tell you which one...it is the first one you pass on the way to the town, on the left. The best guava/cheese pastry and some good sandwiches. And cheap. We ate more fried things than I thought I would ever get sick of. Fried chicken, fried pork, fried fish, fried potatoes, fried plantains, fried ice cream...we couldn't find a vegetable no matter how we searched. I never craved a salad so much. The house salad at our hotel's restaurant consisted of shreds of green and red cabbage and two wedges of albino tomato. Served with a watered down vinaigrette-if you could call it that-it's crunch was it's only grace.I felt for the women who work there...they start the day cooking and setting for breakfast, then move to cleaning the rooms, then back for lunch and dinner. They are all nice and do the best they can with the cheap fixings the owner provides them. Most lunch items are frozen foods reheated, except the quesadilla which is an artery-clogging cheese melt fiesta, but no flavor really. They do put actual alcohol in their $5 pina coladas though so you don't mind that it is a mix they make it with and not local fruit. The staff did try to fix problems when they could..when we got ants in our food stash they sprayed immediately and they were gone for the rest of our stay. When our mini-fridge conked out they switched it right away as well. Not much they could do about barely warm water in the shower and we had to aske every day for extra bath towels. Oh and you have to sign for their very used beach towels-- if you do'nt return them you get charged on your bill. They are better than the provided bath towels but you won't want to keep them.All in all this is an average stay. Your cell phone won't work unless you drive a ways down the road towards the Texaco...if you want to be away from civilization then this will do it. There is a KMart about 25 minutes away and the town of Ponce is about an hour and a half away if you need a casino...but it was all further than we wanted to move after lying in the sun. It is a basic place that wishes it was ritzier but doesn't want to spend on the amenities. But if you want to escape it all and be right on the beach...this is one of the best places in the area. 
